{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> χρή</b>, <br /> <i>impersonal</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.216, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Aeolic dialect</i> <b>χρῆ</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th-6th c.BC: Alcaeus Lyricus 20, 35, 46 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]; other forms are contractions (crases) of χρή (probably originally a <i>neuter</i> <i>substantive</i>) with forms of εἰμί (<b>sum</b>): <i>future</i> χρἤσται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 504, “fragment” 599, 5th c.BC: Pherecrates Comicus 103, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Fragmenta” 362, 5th c.BC: Phrynichus Comicus 34 (on this form, for which codices generally have χρῆσται or χρῆσθαι, see Scholia 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “OC” [same place])\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>subjunctive</i> χρῇ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 999, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Alcestis” 49, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Lysistrata” 133; _optative_ χρείη 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 215, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 162, 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 12.44, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Euthyphro” 4c \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>infinitive</i> χρῆναι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.AD: Democritus Epigrammaticus 276, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ecclesiazusae” 210, 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 5.84, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; also χρῆν (see. below 111); <i>participle</i> <i>neuter</i> <i>plural</i> χρηεόντα (or χρὴ ἐόντα) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.AD: Democritus Epigrammaticus 174 \">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>]: <i>imperfect</i> ἐχρῆν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 7.44, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 907, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 107.6 (only here in 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus, χρῆν l. 5), 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 152, +others, 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 1.1, 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 1.114, 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 3.22, +others, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 6.57, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Protagoras” 335c, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 4.3, +others, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: frequently also without the augment, χρῆν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “Fragmenta.” 123.1, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 529, 579, “Tr.” 1133, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 535 (_anapaest meter_), +others, 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 8.6, +others, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 3.63, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 15.33, +others, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; both forms in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Acharnenses” 540, ἐρεῖ τις, οὐ χρῆν· ἀλλὰ τί ἐχρῆν εἴπατε\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>future</i> χρήδει [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.8 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: —<b>it is necessary</b>: with <i>infinitive</i> praes. aut <i>aorist</i>, <b>it must needs, one must</b> or <b>ought</b> to do (like δεῖ, which is only once used in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus), νῦν δὲ χ. τετλάμεν ἔμπης 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.209; τὸν νῦν χ. κομέειν 6.207, compare 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.216, 4.57, etc.; σήμαιν᾽ ὅ τι χ. σοι συμπράσσειν 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 297 (_anapaest meter_)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὅτι χ. πάσχειν ἐθέλω[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 1067; ὅ τι χρείη ποιεῖν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Euthyphro” 4c, compare 9a; τούτου θανειν χρῆν αὐτὸν οὕνεκ᾽ ἐκ σέθε; 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 579; χρὴ τὸ λέγειν 4th-5th c.BC: Parmenides Poeta Philosophus 6.1 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: more frequently with <i>accusative</i> <i>person</i> et <i>infinitive</i>, <b>one must,</b> ἐμὲ δὲ χ. γήραϊ πείθεσθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 23.644; τῷ σε χ. πόλεμον.. παῦσαι 7.331 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; οὐδέ τί σε χ. νηλεὲς ἦτορ ἔχειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 9.496; τί χ. με.. στέγειν ἢ τί λέγει; 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 135 (Lyric poetry): χρῆν γὰρ Κανδαύλῃ γενέσθαι κακῶς (where γενέσθαι is _infinitive_ of an _impersonal_ verb) 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.8.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]—Sts. the <i>infinitive</i> must be supplied from the context, especially in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus in phrases like{τίπτε μάχης. ἀποπαύεα; οὐδέ τί σε χρή}\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] (i.e. ἀποπαύεσθαι) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 16.721, compare 19.420 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὅθι χ. πεζὸν ἐόντα (i.e. μάρνασθαι) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 9.50 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; so in Trag. and <i>Attic dialect</i>, πορθεῖν ἃ μὴ χ. (i.e. πορθεῖν) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 342 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; φύς τ᾽ ἀφ᾽ ὧν οὐ χρῆν (i.e. φῦναι), ξὺν οἷς τ᾽ οὐ χρῆν (i.e. ὁμιλεῖν) ὁμιλῶν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 1184 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἔκανες ὃν οὐ χρῆν (i.e. κτεῖναι) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 930 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ἐπιπλεύσειέ τις ὡς χ. (i.e. ἐπιπλεῦσαι) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.89 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; θύσαντες οἷς χ. (i.e. θῦσαι) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 415e; ἀκαιρότερον ὄντα ἢ χ. [prev. author] “Plt.” 307e; λαλεῖν μετὰ ἀφελείας ἔνθα χ. 3rd c.AD: Longinus Rhetor 34.2.; so ὡς χ. 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1556 (_anapaest meter_), etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] —The <i>imperfect</i> frequently expresses something that ought to have been, but is not, ἐνθάδ᾽ οὐ παραστατεῖ, ὡς χρῆν, Ὀρέστης[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 879, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 1133; and sometimes stands for χρή, χρῆν τι λέγειν ὑμᾶς σοφὸν ῳ νικήσετε 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 487 (_anapaest meter_), compare 432: _absolutely_, ἐρεῖτις, οὐ χρῆν· ἀλλὰτί ἐχρῆν εἴπατε [prev. author] “Ach.” 540. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus without \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<i>infinitive</i>, with <i>accusative</i> <i>person</i> et <i>genitive</i> <i>of things</i>, οὐδέ τί σε χρὴ ἀφρποσύνης thou <b>hast</b> no <b>need of</b> imprudence, i. e. it does not <b>befit</b> thee, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.109; οὐ μέν σε χ. ἔτ᾽ αἰδοῦς 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.14; τί με χ. μητέρος αἴνο; 21.110 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; μυθήσεαι ὅττεό (i.e. ὅτου) σε χ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1.124; τέο σε χ.; 4.463: τί χρὴ φίλων\">Refs</a>] is found in most codices of [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Orestes” 667 (δεῖ codex V). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> with <i>dative</i> <i>person</i> pro <i>accusative</i> is not found; in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 5.490, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 3 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], the <i>dative</i> belongs to the <i>infinitive</i> μέλει; in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 736 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] Dobree restored με for γ; in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 886 ᾗ\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] depends on μετεῖνα; in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Ion” 1316 Dobree read τοὺς δέ γ᾽ ἐνδίκους, and in 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 28.10 δικαίους.. ὑφελομένους was restored by Cobet. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> sometimes in a less strong sense, πῶς τοῦτο περᾶσαι χρ; how <b>is one to</b> get through this? [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 15.45 \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; τί ἐχρῆν με ποιεῖ; what <b>was I to</b> do? [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 18.28 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ἓν οὐδὲν κατέστη ἴαμα ὅτι χρῆν προσφερόντας ὠφελεῖν there was no one remedy by the application of which one <b>could</b> (or <b>was bound to</b>) help them, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.51, compare 1.91. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> τὸ χρῆν (<i>infinitive</i>) <b>fate, destiny,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hecuba” 260 (assuming variant, τὸ χρὴ Nauck)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὸ χρή [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “HF” 828 \">Refs</a>]; conjecture for τὸ χρεών (<i>monosyllable</i>) in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “fragment” 733.3, “IT” 1486. \">Refs</a>]","strongNumber":"G5534","accentedUnicode":"χρή","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G5531","matchingForm":"χράω","stepTransliteration":"chraō","gloss":"to lend","_zh_tw_Gloss":"請借給","_es_Gloss":"prestar","_zh_Gloss":"请借给"},{"strongNumber":"G5532","matchingForm":"χρεία","stepTransliteration":"chreia","gloss":"need","_zh_tw_Gloss":"需要, 用, 需","_es_Gloss":"necesidad","_zh_Gloss":"需要, 用, 需"},{"strongNumber":"G5535","matchingForm":"χρῄζω","stepTransliteration":"chrēzō","gloss":"to need","_zh_tw_Gloss":"所需用","_es_Gloss":"necesitar","_zh_Gloss":"所需用"}],"shortDef":"it should, it is necessary","mediumDef":"it should, it is necessary <br />impersonal verb, <b>there is need</b> or <b>occasion, it is necessary, it is requisite; it becomes, it is proper,</b> <ref='Jas.3.10'>Jas. 3:10</ref>*","stepGloss":"to ought/n